 political interests within the community, how racial consciousness provided an axis for social solidarity as well as partial insulation from racial slights, and how the suburb afforded these middle-class residents a degree of physical and social distance from the ghetto. As Haynes explores the history of Runyon Heights, we learn the ways in which its black middle class dealt with the tensions between the political interests of race and the material interests of class.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAfrican AmericanszNew York (State)zYonkersxEconomic conditions. 0aAfrican AmericanszNew York (State)zYonkersxHistory. 0aAfrican AmericanszNew York (State)zYonkersxSocial conditions. 0aMiddle classzNew York (State)zYonkersxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / African American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831105379940 cprintz978030008490040uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030012986140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300129861423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300129861/original  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY